5.Literature Review:-
The Evolution of Core Banking Architectures:-
The historical development of core banking systems is marked by clear shifts in technology and operational design. The first generation of computerized core systems emerged in the 1970s, designed to replace manual, paper-based ledger entries on mainframe computers. These early platforms were product-specific and relied on batch processing models.
Transactions executed during the business day were queued and run during sequential "End of Day" (EoD), "Close of Business" (CoB), "End of Month" (EoM), or "End of Year" (EoY) batch windows. Because account balances were updated only after the batch cycle completed, real-time balance visibility was impossible, and transactions across branches remained slow.
The second generation, which emerged in the 1980s and 1990s, introduced package-based software built on relational databases. While these systems improved product configuration capabilities, they remained monolithic in design. They were typically built on proprietary mainframes using COBOL, prioritizing transaction consistency and high-volume stability over flexibility.
As digital banking expanded in the 2000s, these monolithic cores required elaborate, custom-built middleware and point-to-point integrations to connect with digital frontends, which introduced significant technical debt and increased system complexity.

The Core Talent Deficit and Technical Debt:-
A major operational challenge driving the modernization of core banking platforms is the decline in legacy programming expertise. While a significant portion of global transaction volume still runs on COBOL engines hosted on mainframes, the global pool of skilled mainframe developers and legacy database administrators is retiring rapidly. This trend creates a knowledge vacuum within traditional banks, making the maintenance of legacy core software increasingly expensive and risky.
Furthermore, younger software engineering talent is highly resistant to working with antiquated technologies, preferring modern cloud-native architectures. By modernizing to modern technology stacks (such as Java, Go, and relational or non-relational database models), financial institutions can attract top-tier technical talent, leverage automated DevOps pipelines, and lower core platform maintenance costs.

Composable Architectures and Headless Cores:-
To address the limitations of legacy systems, modern core developments favor composable, service-oriented, and "headless" designs. A headless core banking system decouples the back-end ledger engine from the customer-facing frontend channels, with communication managed through standardized APIs.
Traditional monolithic applications bundle the user interface and transaction processing rules into a single codebase, meaning minor frontend changes require compiling and deploying the entire core system. Decoupled architectures address this constraint, allowing banks to update front-end channels rapidly without risking the operational stability of the central ledger.
This architectural transition is highly relevant due to the rise of Frontend-as-a-Service (FaaS) and open banking. Monolithic frontends often face slow update cycles due to native platform modifications and app store review processes, which can delay the deployment of new digital financial products. Decoupling the front and back ends resolves these integration bottlenecks, allowing banks to easily integrate with third-party FinTech ecosystems, payment gateways, and digital marketplaces.


Emerging Technological Trends in 2026 and Beyond:-
The evolution of core banking systems in 2026 is driven by several modern technological trends:
Agentic AI and Predictive Treasuries: The integration of autonomous artificial intelligence directly into core ledger systems has transformed traditional reactive accounting into predictive treasury operations. AI agents monitor real-time FX spreads, analyze liquidity levels across global sub-accounts, and execute automated hedging transactions to optimize capital utilization and protect operating margins.

Quantum Computing Preparation: As quantum computing advances, leading financial institutions are developing quantum-secure transactional frameworks. Core systems must prepare to adopt quantum-resistant cryptographic standards to protect transaction histories and tokenized financial assets from decryption threats.

Embedded Finance and Open Banking: Core engines are shifting toward open, multi-rail API environments that embed banking capabilities directly into non-financial platforms, allowing corporate partners to execute instant transactions at the point of sale.












