Idempotency Protocol in Distributed Core Systems:-

Strict Use of Idempotency Keys: Every incoming transaction request is assigned a unique identifier (e.g., a UUID or generated trace number). The distributed system stores this key alongside the transaction’s status. If a client sends a duplicate request, the CBS identifies the existing key and returns the initial response instead of debiting the account again.
State Verification & Duplicate Prevention: Before executing any money movement or balance updates, the CBS queries its persistent data store to verify if the unique transaction ID has already been successfully executed. This stops redundant financial processing at the ledger level and guarantees the final state remains consistent.
Caching with Distributed Locks: When concurrent requests with the identical idempotency key hit the CBS simultaneously, the system applies temporary distributed locks (or atomic database constraints). This serializes the operations so that only the first request is executed, while the subsequent concurrent requests wait to retrieve the cached result of the first.

